@ptrendx 
I think, Tensor op internal calculation method is FP16, not FP32. You can refer to the following document diagram.
![](https://pic2.zhimg.com/v2-f898adc567dac88a7d6e05432b7cce2d_r.jpg "TensorOp")

@ptrendx 
OK, I got 3.33x speedup between V100-tensor with P40 in resnet-50 network.
Thank you for your assistant.

It is possible that the bug is specific to OSX, but it could also be that the particular layout of the heap in your environment does not trigger the bug.

I find that if I add I make the auxiliary states larger and have more of them, it crashes every time on my machine using latest prerelease build (0.12.1b20171115).

~~~
import mxnet as mx

class BadAux(mx.operator.CustomOp):
    def forward(self, is_train, req, in_data, out_data, aux):
        self.assign(out_data[0], req[0], in_data[0][0])


@mx.operator.register('bad-aux')
class BadAuxProp(mx.operator.CustomOpProp):
    def __init__(self):
        super(BadAuxProp, self).__init__(need_top_grad=False)

    def infer_shape(self, in_shape):
        out_shape = [(1,)]
        aux_shape = [(100,)] * 7
        return in_shape, out_shape, aux_shape

    def list_arguments(self):
        return ['data']

    def list_auxiliary_states(self):
        return ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e','f','g']

    def declare_backward_dependency(self, out_grad, in_data, out_data):
        return []

    def create_operator(self, ctx, in_shapes, in_dtypes):
        return BadAux()


q = mx.nd.Custom(mx.nd.ones((10000,)),
                 mx.nd.zeros((100,)),
                 mx.nd.zeros((100,)),
                 mx.nd.zeros((100,)),
                 mx.nd.zeros((100,)),
                 mx.nd.zeros((100,)),
                 mx.nd.zeros((100,)),
                 mx.nd.zeros((100,)),
                 op_type='bad-aux')

print(q)
